title: ‘I almost threw up’: Albanese’s ‘sickening’ Joy Division t-shirt shamed
description: Sky News host Rowan Dean claims he was “sickened” by seeing Prime Minister Anthony Albanese’s “extremely disturbing” Joy Division t-shirt.   “The moment I saw that photo of Anthony Albanese coming down the steps from a very successful international meeting … wearing a t-shirt with the words Joy Division,” Mr Dean said.  “I immediately almost threw up when I saw that image.”

title: ‘Cold peace’: Trump-Xi talks push things in the ‘right direction’
description: Former White House chief of staff Mick Mulvaney says US President Donald Trump’s discussion with Chinese Leader Xi Jinping is pushing things in the “right direction”.  “This is more of a cold peace, and now there is a détente, and they’ll end up trying to continue the conversation, and that’s why I think there is tremendous value here,” Mr Mulvaney told Sky News host James Morrow.  “It’s not peace in our time; it’s the beginning of the discussion, and it sounds like things are moving in the right direction.”

title: Zohran Mamdani’s mother exposes him as ‘not American at all’
description: Sky News host James Morrow has reacted to a report from the New York Post which revealed Democrat New York mayoral candidate Zohran Mamdani’s mother described him as “not an American at all”.  “Your paper reported that Zohran Mamdani’s mother, who, herself, is quite a prominent filmmaker, said that she thinks of her son as ‘not an American at all’ – her words,” Mr Morrow said.  “Others have seized on his comments about 9/11 and talking about his aunt, who wasn’t actually his aunt, who said she felt uncomfortable taking the train after 9/11 because she wore a hijab.  “I’m glad he identified who the real victims of that terror attack was.”

title: Left-wing media reaction ‘hysterical’ after Trump announces nuclear testing restart
description: Centre of the American Experiment President John Hinderaker comments on the media’s reaction to US President Donald Trump’s announcement that the country will kickstart its nuclear testing program.  “It’s been hysterical, the liberal press make it sound like World War III is about to break out and it’s all Trump’s fault,” Mr Hinderaker told Sky News host Rowan Dean.  “Frankly, we have this big nuclear arsenal, but we haven’t tested it; we haven’t tested anything in 33 years.  “I think it’s probably a good idea for us to test a few of these nuclear weapons and see if they actually still work.”

title: ‘Scrambling for alternatives’: Trump seeks to reduce US reliance on Chinese minerals
description: Centre of the American Experiment President John Hinderaker weighs in on the meeting between US President Donald Trump and Chinese President Xi Jinping.   “The real significance is he [Donald Trump] got a one-year delay in China’s export restrictions on rare earths,” Mr Hinderaker told Sky News host Rowan Dean.  “United States has gotten itself into this terrible position where we are dependent on the Communist Chinese for many of the most vital minerals that we need for our economy.  “The Trump administration is really scrambling to find alternative sources, as well as to develop American mining.  “I think that’s mostly what this is about, the strategic importance of our access to those minerals.”

title: ‘Complete and utter disgrace’: Nigel Farage heckled in parliament while presenting bill
description: Reform UK Councillor Darren Grimes responds to his party leader Nigel Farage being heckled in parliament while presenting a bill, describing the incident as a “complete and utter disgrace”.   “That’s a complete and utter disgrace … it’s a perfect snapshot of the rot within Westminster,” Mr Grimes told Sky News host Danica De Giorgio.  “The moment that someone actually defends Britain and our borders, the establishment actually turns into a pack of playground bullies showing themselves to be completely removed from the concerns of the British public.   “How dare they sit there and laugh? They are laughing at the British public.”

title: ‘Coronation of common sense’: Prince Andrew stripped of royal titles
description: Reform UK Councillor Darren Grimes reacts to Prince Andrew being stripped of his royal titles, calling the move “two decades too late”.   “I think actually, there’s been a sort of collective outreach saying look, this is two decades too late,” Mr Grimes told Sky News host Danica De Giorgio.  “Ordinary Brits, I think, are actually cheering this on … it’s the coronation of common sense.  “King Charles has finally taken out the palace pest, someone who actually, I think, has disgraced the institution.”

title: ‘Send him back to DJing’: Albanese’s ‘disgraceful’ Joy Division shirt under spotlight
description: Former Liberal senator Hollie Hughes claims Prime Minister Anthony Albanese’s Joy Division t-shirt was “disgraceful”.   “This is a man who is supposed to be the leader of our country,” Ms Hughes told Sky News host Rowan Dean.  “We need to send him back out on the road, and he can go DJing again.”

title: ‘He is acting as King, not as brother’: Charles had ‘no choice’ but to strip Andrew from titles
description: Former speaker of the house Bronwyn Bishop thinks King Charles had “no choice” but to strip Prince Andrew of his royal titles.  “Once those emails started to come out … he had to act,” Ms Bishop told Sky News host Rowan Dean.  “He is acting as the King, not as a brother.  “I really don’t think he had any option.”

title: ‘Biggest royal scandal in history’: King Charles stripping Andrew from his titles is a first
description: Sky News contributor Adrian Hayes weighs in on King Charles stripping Prince Andrew’s royal titles.   “It was surprising,” Mr Hayes told Sky News host Steve Price.  “Nothing like this has happened for hundreds of years.”  Mr Hayes claims King Charles’ move “hopefully” puts Andrew’s involvement with Jeffrey Epstein to “an end”.

title: ‘No love lost for him’: Andrew’s popularity has been at an ‘all time low’ since BBC interview
description: Sky News contributor Adrian Hayes claims Prince Andrew, now Andrew Mountbatten Windsor, and his popularity “nosedived” after his infamous BBC interview.   “His fall was gradual, but it was after that interview on the BBC,” Mr Hayes told Sky News host Steve Price.   “His judgments were just so appalling.  “His popularity is at an all-time low.  “There is no love lost for Andrew at all.”

title: ‘A basket case’: Jacinta Allan blasted for ‘ignoring voters’ over Indigenous treaty bill
description: Indigenous leader Warren Mundine criticises the Victorian government for “ignoring” voters after the state passed its Indigenous treaty bill.  “Even if you are a treaty supporter, it doesn’t recognise Aboriginal culture, it doesn’t recognise traditional owners, and it’s just another body that the Labor Party has set up,” Mr Mundine told Sky News host Steve Price.  “I’m not surprised that the Jacinta Allan government has ignored that; they’ve been ignoring the economy for a long time, and you can see the state is just a basket case.”

title: ‘Preposterous, outrageous lie’: Liberals urged to ‘wake up’ to net zero debate
description: Former Queensland premier Campbell Newman urges the Liberal Party to “wake up to themselves” on the issue of net zero.  “Until the Liberal Party, and perhaps elements of the National Party still, wake up to themselves and prepare to actually go out and fight and make an argument, they’re not going to get anywhere,” Mr Newman told Sky News host Steve Price.  “They should be saying net zero is a preposterous, outrageous lie, it will not achieve anything in terms of climate … it is going to destroy Australia economically.”

title: World’s Gone Mad: Karine Jean-Pierre continues her DEI rampage
description: Sky News host Rowan Dean criticises former White House press secretary Karine Jean-Pierre for repeatedly highlighting her race and sexuality during her book tour.

title: World’s Gone Mad: Deranged conspiracy theorist claims aliens are on Earth
description: Sky News host Rowan Dean mocks a conspiracy theorist’s bizarre claim that aliens are living on Earth.
